oldact.en:
60CC How a court determines what is in a child's best interests
(1) The court must consider the matters in subsections (2) and (3).
(2) PRIMARY considerations:
(a) the benefit to the child of a meaningful relationship with both of the child's parents; and
(b) the need to protect the child from physical or psychological harm from abuse, neglect or family violence.
(2A) The court is to give GREATER WEIGHT to (2)(b) [protection from harm].
(3) ADDITIONAL considerations include:
(a) any views expressed by the child (and the child's maturity/understanding);
(b) the nature of the child's relationship with each parent and others;
(c) the extent each parent participated in major long-term decisions, spent time and communicated with the child;
(ca) the extent each parent met maintenance obligations;
(d) the likely effect of changes in the child's circumstances (incl. separation from a parent or significant person);
… and further factors (e)–(m).

act.en:
60CC How a court determines what is in a child's best interests
(2) General considerations — the court must consider:
(a) what arrangements would promote the safety (incl. from family violence, abuse, neglect or other harm) of the child and each carer;
(b) any views expressed by the child;
(c) the developmental, psychological, emotional and cultural needs of the child;
(d) the capacity of each person who has/ is to have parental responsibility to provide for those needs;
(e) the benefit to the child of a relationship with the child's parents and other significant people, where safe;
(f) anything else relevant.
(2A) Must also consider any history of family violence, abuse or neglect, and any family violence order.
(3) Additional considerations — the child's right to enjoy Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander culture.

